Even with type hinting It&#39;s often useful to annotate a variable as a typed array (especially for parameters):

```php
/**
 * @param int[] $bars
 */
function foo(array $bars)
{
    foreach ($bars as $bar) {
        // int stuff
    }
}
```

But if the variable is only used for a foreach loop, it&#39;s better to write the code for [iterables](https://www.php.net/manual/en/language.types.iterable.php).

Is there a clean way to annotate a typed iterable? `@param int iterable`

Properly naming the variable is the obvious solution: `function foo(iterable $ints)`, but sometimes it could be one of several types (that don&#39;t share inheritance): 

```

```php
/**
 * @param MyCustomClass[]|MyOtherClass[] $bars
 */
function foo(iterable $myCustomClasses_Or_MyOtherClasses)
{
    foreach ($myCustomClasses_Or_MyOtherClasses as $myCustomClass_Or_MyOtherClass) {
...
```

It&#39;s possible to type hint the parameter with `iterable` while annotating a typed array:

```php
/**
 * @param int[] $bars
 */
function foo(iterable $bars)
...
```

But I find that needlessly confusing, and it doesn&#39;t cover cases such as `@return` and `@var`

I&#39;ve found info about array types ([on phpdoc.org](https://docs.phpdoc.org/guides/types.html) and several questions on SO), but nothing on iterable typing.

