In a real life, you write a function like this once and just reuse it when needed. To be generic enough, our `groupBy` should accept another &quot;key&quot; function, so that we can &quot;group&quot; by any property or just some ad-hoc computed value. Besides that, an Object is not the best option for storing groups, because our values are not guaranteed to be primitives anymore. Therefore, let&#39;s use a `Map` instead:

    function groupBy(it, keyFunc) {

        let groups = new Map();

        for (let x of it) {
            let k = keyFunc(x);
            if (!groups.has(k))
                groups.set(k, []);
            groups.get(k).push(x);
        }

        return groups;
    }

